Problem Statement¶

The sinking of the RMS Titanic is one of the most infamous shipwrecks in history. On April 15, 1912, during her maiden voyage, the Titanic sank after colliding with an iceberg, killing numerous passengers and crew. This sensational tragedy shocked the international community and led to better safety regulations for ships.
One of the reasons that the shipwreck led to such loss of life was that there were not enough lifeboats for the passengers and crew. Although there was some element of luck involved in surviving the sinking, some groups of people were more likely to survive than others, such as women, children, and the upper-class.
In this, we ask you to complete the analysis of what sorts of people were likely to survive. In particular, we ask you to apply the tools of machine learning to predict which passengers survived the tragedy.

**Data Description**¶

survived == Survival == 0 : No, 1 : Yes
Pclass == Ticket class == 1 : 1st, 2 : 2nd, 3 : 3rd
Sex == Sex
Age == Age in years
Sibsp == # of siblings / spouses aboard the Titanic
Parch == # of parents / children aboard the Titanic
Ticket == Ticket number
Fare == Passenger fare
Cabin == Cabin number
embarked == Port of Embarkation == C : Cherbourg, Q : Queenstown, S : Southampton

**Process**¶

  1. Import Libraries

#replace various titles with more common ones, Rare ones with 'Ot' i.e. Others, Royals to 'Ryl' & Master to 'Mst'

data_1['Title'] = data_1['Title'].replace(['Countess', 'Lady', 'Sir'], 'Ryl')
data_1['Title'] = data_1['Title'].replace('Mlle', 'Ms')
data_1['Title'] = data_1['Title'].replace('Ms', 'Ms')
data_1['Title'] = data_1['Title'].replace('Mme', 'Mrs')
data_1['Title'] = data_1['Title'].replace('Master', 'Mst')

data_1["Age_Mod"] = data_1["Age"].fillna(-0.5) # Missing value populated

# labels as per general demography split
data_1['Age_Group'] = pd.cut(data_1["Age_Mod"], age_bins, labels = age_labels)

Cabin Number

Defining Deck with help of Cabin Number¶

People with higher socioeconomic class will have recorded cabin numbers; i.e. better/safer accomodation; increasing their chances of survival. Looking further into this assumption

In [37]:
data_1["Cabin_Bool"] = (data_1["Cabin"].notnull().astype('int'))

#calculate percentages of CabinBool vs. survived
CabBol = (data_1["Survived"][data_1["Cabin_Bool"] == 1].value_counts(normalize = True)[1]*100)
NoBol = (data_1["Survived"][data_1["Cabin_Bool"] == 0].value_counts(normalize = True)[1]*100)
print("%age of Passangers WITH recorded cabin numbers who survived:",CabBol.round(2),"%")

Passangers with recorded cabin numbers are more likely to survive, hence defining the available cabin numbers as Deck; indicating cabin position on ship

Feature Engineering & UniVariate - BiVariate Analysis

Feature Engineering

Features Created so far:

  1. Title : Defines Title of Names of Passangers
  2. Cat_Title : Categorization of 'Title'
  3. Age_Mod : Copy of Original Age column for further computations
  4. Age_Group : Categorization of Age, to handle missing Age values
  5. Cat_Age : Numeric categorization of Age_Group
  6. Cabin_Bool : Column created to check if boolean prefix is present for Cabin Column, to handle missing Cabin values
  7. Deck : Column created out of boolean prefix of Cabin Column, to handle missing Cabin values
  8. Cat_Deck : Numeric categorization of Deck

Family Size

We have observed so far that Parch and SibSp are highly corelated, hence both features cannot be used; however both contain different set of information i.e. Number of Parents / Children & Number of Siblings / Spouse aboard Titanic. Put together it can indicate family size of the Passanger. Hence creating new feature by adding both values.

Insights

Key :

  1. Survived :::: 0 = No, 1 = Yes
  2. Pclass :::: 1 = 1st Class, 2 = 2nd Class, 3 = 3rd Class
  3. Cat_Embarked :::: Numeric representation of Embarked :: 0 = 'C' - Cherbourg, 1 = 'Q' - Queenstown, 2 = 'S' - Southampton
  4. Cat_Title :::: Numeric representation of Title :: 1 = Mr, 2 = Ms, 3 = Mrs, 4 = Mst, 5 = Ryl, 6 = Ot
  5. Age_Group :::: Numeric calculation of age grouping :: Infant = 0-5yr, Child = 5-12yr, Teenager = 12-18yr, Young Adult = 18-24yr, Adult = 24-35yr, Senior Adult = 35-60yr, Old = 60+yrs
  6. Cat_Age :::: Numeric representation of Age_Group :: 1 = Infant, 2 = Child, 3 = Teenager, 4 = Young Adult, 5 = Adult, 6 = Senior Adult, 7 = Old
  7. Cabin_Bool :::: Numeric value after computation of Cabin prefix :: 0 = Prefix Not Available in Cabin Number, 1 = Prefix Available in Cabin Number
  8. Deck :::: A, B, C, D, E, F, G, T, NA = A-T prefix of Cabin number idicating cabin place on the ship, NA = prefix of Cabin number not there, hence categorized all such cases in 1 and named NA
  9. Cat_Deck :::: Numeric representation of Deck :: 1 = A, 2= B, 3 = C, 4 = D, 5 = E, 6 = F, 7 = G, 8 = T, 9 = NA
  10. FamilySize :::: Neaumaric value after computation SipSp + Parch + 1 - passanger himself
  11. Group_FamilySize :::: Large > 4 members, Small 2 to 4 members, Solo = 1 passanger - on board Titanic
  12. Cat_Family :::: Numeric representation of Group_FamilySize :: 0 = Large, 1 = Small, 2 = Solo
  13. Fare_Group :::: Neaumaric calculation of fare grouping :: 1 = 0-25$, 2 = 25-50$, 3 = 50-75$, 4 = 75-100$, 5 = 100-125$, 6 = 125-150$, 7 = 150-175$, 8 = >175$
  14. Cat_Gender :::: LabelEncoder Sex
  15. Cat_Embarked :::: LabelEncoder Embarked

Getting Dummies for Sex & Embarked only, as rest all categorical variables created are in a logical incremental order, as of now planning to maintain the same

y_pred_test = decisiontree.predict(X_test)
y_pred_train = decisiontree.predict(X_train)
acc_decisiontree_test = round(accuracy_score(y_pred_test, y_test) * 100, 2)
acc_decisiontree_train = round(accuracy_score(y_pred_train, y_train) * 100, 2)
print("Decision Tree Test Data Accuracy : ", acc_decisiontree_test)
print("Decision Tree Train Data Accuracy : ", acc_decisiontree_train)

Decision Tree Test Data Accuracy :  82.12
Decision Tree Train Data Accuracy :  78.79

Insights

Fitted Model with all input variables and selected features, accuracy remained the same hence, concluded to use only selected features.
As indicated in Predictions section, Models with best accuracy are Decision Tree, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting; however considering both the Accuracy scores for Test and Train data, Decision Tree can be concluded the one with best Accuracy score on both Test and Train data

Conclusion : Decision Tree Classification Model.
